text: The potential of VCD to resolve the epimer vs. inverse epimer quandary Karel D. Klika a,⇑ a Department of Chemistry, University of Turku, Vatselankatu 2, FIN-20014, Turku, Finland b Department of Biochemistry and Food Chemistry, University of Turku, Vatselankatu 2, FIN-20014, Turku, Finland Article history: Received 16 April 2012 Received in revised form 23 May 2012 Accepted 23 May 2012 Available online 2 June 2012 Keywords: Epimer Inverse epimer Stereochemistry Density functional theory Vibrational circular dichroism In recent studies [1] we encountered the problem of distin- guishing between a pair of stereoisomers with respect to whether they constitute a pair of epimers or, alternatively, a pair of inverse epimers. The latter have been deﬁned [1a] as: ‘‘Inverse epimers are stereoisomers containing more than two stereogenic centers that differ in their conﬁguration at all stereogenic centers bar one. In other words, the inverse of the epimeric case’’. This assignment of rela- tive stereochemistry can be unexpectedly obdurate and is resilient to clariﬁcation by achiral NMR.

Naturally occurring alnumycin [2] {originally described as a sin- gle compound [2a–c], then a pair of stereoisomers [2d], then as a set of six stereoisomeric compounds alnumycins A1–3 (1–3) [1]; see Ref. [1a] for a summation of the history of alnumycin and the various names associated with the structure} is an especially inter- esting member of the class of bacterial aromatic polyketides since, instead of the common attendant sidechain deoxysugars – neces- sary for the expression of biological activity and favorable solubil- ity characteristics – it possesses a highly unusual 40-hydroxy-50- hydroxymethyl-20,70-dioxane moiety which is, furthermore, at- tached atypically via a CAC bond to the isochromanequinone agly- cone (viz. prealnumycin, 4). The bacterial aromatic polyketides are well known for their biological properties and have a number of established medicinal applications [3], including use as antibiotics. The determination of whether two stereoisomers constitute a pair of epimers or if they differ in their conﬁguration at all stereogenic centers bar one can be a formidable challenge and represent a problem of greater complexity than just determination of absolute conﬁguration per se. The latter case has been deﬁned as a pair of inverse epimers and is exempliﬁed by the naturally occurring compounds alnumycins A1–3. The potential of vibrational circular dichroism (VCD) for discerning between pairs of epimers or inverse epimers has been considered in principle for the alnumycin A1 pair and the C-1 epimer of A1a (ent-A1b) by DFT-calculated spectra obtained at the M06-2X/6-31G(d) level of theory. It was concluded that the application holds much promise for the task at hand and can overcome the shortcomings asso- ciated with other techniques, in particular with respect to their limited generality. highlight the conundrum in distinguishing between a case of epi- mers or a case of inverse epimers for 1a and 1b would otherwise constitute a pair of enantiomers if it were not for the stereogenic center at C-1. Indeed, it was the special relationship between 1a and 1b – in that they differ from each other in their conﬁgurations at all stereogenic centers bar one – that led to the genesis of the concept of inverse epimers [1a]. Since C-1 is quite distant from the other stereogenic centers all located in the dioxane ring, there is only a minimal interaction between C-1 and the remaining ste- reogenic centers resulting in exceedingly similar NMR spectra for 1a and 1b. In fact, the spectra of alnumycin A1–3 (1–3) were remarkable in that for most signals it was extremely difﬁcult, nigh on impossible, to gauge the presence of a pair of stereoisomers de- spite the ﬁne linewidth of some signal lines. The results were found to be very concentration, solvent, and temperature dependent. Apparent splittings could also be easily confused with couplings in many cases due to the presence of stereoisomers. Thus the rec- ognition of the presence of stereoisomers is dependent on many factors including also a high dependency on the acquisition and processing parameters as well as B0 homogeneity given the ex- treme similarity of the compounds. Further details are given in Ref. [1b]. Indeed, the close similarity of the stereoisomer pairs elic- its the description of them as ‘‘near enantiomers’’ of each other.

For 1a (1R,10R,40R,50S) and 1b (1R,10S,40S,50R), since they differ at all stereogenic centers bar C-1, they are most conveniently de- scribed C-1 inverse epimers [1a]. The intriguing question is, upon encountering compound pairs such as 1a and 1b (or 2a and 2b, 3a and 3b, etc.), do the two stereoisomers constitute a pair of epi- mers or a pair of inverse epimers? This is because E and IE are enantiomers of one another (IE = ent-E). This concept is depicted in Fig. 2 using the conﬁgurations for the pair of stereoisomers originally reported by Tatsuta et al. [2d].

It is worth pointing out that the complexity of effecting a dis- tinction is not simpliﬁed by the proximity of the stereogenic center in question (the chiral center that changes in the case of epimers or is invariant in the case of inverse epimers) to the other stereogenic centers. It does hold though, that whether a compound and its epi- mer or inverse epimer exhibit large discernible differences to one another such as spectral or physicochemical properties is depen- dent on the disposition of the stereogenic center in question and its interaction with the other stereogenic centers in the molecule. However, irrespective of whether the observed property differ- ences are large or not, the likely premise of a considerable chal- lenge remain insurmountable by achiral NMR even if the C-1 stereogenic center was proximal to the dioxane ring in 1 [1a]. Indeed, close proximity Fig. 2. Schematic indicating the stereochemical relationships between alnumycins A1a (1a) and A1b (1b) and the C-1 epimer of 1a (ent-1b). may even compromise the analysis [1b]. This is not to be confused with the implication that the very presence of two stereoisomers is likely to be more apparent the more proximal the C-1 stereogenic center is to the dioxane ring [1a]. To effect the distinction, either chirooptical methods {e.g. OR, electronic circular dichroism (ECD), or vibrational circular dichroism (VCD)}, X-ray diffraction, chiral-sensitive methods {e.g. NMR using either chiral derivatizing agents (CDAs) or chiral solvating agents (CSAs)}, or even asymmet- ric synthesis, is requisite. Indeed, such an analysis can transcend the determination of the absolute conﬁguration of enantiomers gi- ven that the determination of one enantiomer yields the other by default whereas for this scenario, both compounds are required to have their absolute conﬁgurations independently determined, with the presence of enantiomers only compounding matters. In the case at hand however, the particular structural features of the alnumycins A1–3 (1–3) fortuitously enabled the ready deter- mination of the pairs as inverse epimers rather than epimers by ECD measurements [1] (in addition to the determination of the absolute conﬁgurations of C-1) in conjunction with theoretical cal- culations using time-dependent density functional theory (TD- DFT) at the M06-2X/6-311+G(d) level of theory. The conclusions regarding epimeric or inverse-epimeric relationships were then further conﬁrmed [1b], together with rendering of the holemicity of the C-1 stereogenic center, by application of the CDA Mosher’s acid chloride [6] {a-methoxy-a-triﬂuorophenylacetyl chloride (MTPACl)} to effect enantiodifferentiation [7]. This latter term has been deﬁned [7] as: ‘‘Enantiodifferentiation is the identiﬁcation of an enantiomer, the quantiﬁcation of enantiomeric composition, and/or the determination of absolute conﬁguration’’.

As an aside, applying Ockham’s razor in scenarios such as the one portrayed here would intimate that a pair of C-1 epimers would prevail over a pair of inverse epimers since the latter re- quires conﬁgurational changes at a number of centers instead of just one. One can speculate on the number of times workers may have simply assumed that an epimeric relationship must be in ef- fect without conclusively conﬁrming it. Though the epimer/inverse epimer evaluations were highly suc- cessful in this instance, there are, however, problems and limita- tions with the two aforementioned techniques with regards to generality. In the case of ECD, the need for a suitable chromophore to be present and one whose ECD spectrum was dependent on only the conﬁguration of one stereogenic center (or one set of stereogen- ic centers) and independent of the other stereogenic centers (or the one stereogenic center in question). In the case of CDAs, the need for invariance in the conformation of the substrate and the acknowl- edged preferred conformations of the CDA [6a,8] as well as both a lack of steric and magnetic interactions in the case of multiple derivatization [1b,8b,9]. Needless to say, there must also not be a lack of suitable derivatizable functional groups for the attachment of the CDA. These limitations compelled us to seek other alterna- tives, e.g. VCD, that would constitute general techniques to solve the question at hand, viz. to discern between stereoisomer pairs as either epimers or inverse epimers, and that would circumvent the shortcomings inherent in the ECD and CDAs techniques.

Ever since the initial reports describing [10] and then conﬁrm- ing VCD [11], the usefulness of VCD has been well recognized [12] and example reports of the practical application of VCD to solving chemical problems abound. Indeed, the determination of absolute conﬁguration by the application of VCD in conjunction with calcu- lations has become a well-established practice [13–18]. DFT calcu- lations in particular, are represented by numerous examples in the literature [12a,c,19] and the application has matured strongly since the seminal reports of Cheeseman et al. [15]. Moreover, VCD has not just been used for the determination of absolute conﬁguration of molecules and other enantiodifferentiation aspects, applications have also been extended to include diasterodifferentiation [14,18], conformational analysis [14,16,17,20], the study of secondary structure of biomolecules [21], and even, somewhat enigmatically, the determination of constitutional isomerism [16]. The advantages of VCD include its relatively sharp signals in comparison to ECD where the bands are so broad as to completely hide substantial structural information in many instances. Indeed, ECD is often viewed as a ‘‘molecular-whole’’ property, or at least limited to the chromophore, whereas VCD, importantly, has associ- ated with it a sense of locality for the bands which can thus be associated with a particular stereogenic center(s). For molecules that lack a suitable chromophore and for which ECD is thus inap- plicable, VCD will, in principle at least, always have suitable bands for analysis. These advantages of VCD over ECD have been similarly enunciated by others [13,18]. Similarly too, optical rotation is gen- erally, with rare exception [1a], viewed as a ‘‘molecular-whole’’ property. In comparison to ECD, VCD calculations are generally more amenable and are a readily available option in a number of quantum chemical program packages. Serious drawbacks for VCD include the availability to measure spectra as instruments are still uncommon and the relative insensitivity of the measurement (e.g. in comparison to ECD when applicable).

In this work, the potential of VCD to discern between a case of a pair of epimers or a pair of inverse epimers was considered in prin- ciple for alnumycins A1a (1a) and A1b (1b) and the C-1 epimer of 1a (ent-1b) by DFT-calculated spectra obtained at the M06-2X/6- 31G(d) level of theory since, although it is non-intuitive, it is not possible to accomplish this by achiral NMR. The distinction be- tween epimer and inverse epimer pairs would represent a new application of VCD and, moreover, the potential to acquire spectra of mixtures of diastereoisomers and still obtain meaningful struc- tural interpretation is a novel aspect of the utilization. The unlikely paradox is that the nominal pursuit at least of absolute conﬁgura- tion – though not necessarily assigning it – is being made in order to effect a relative conﬁguration relationship. It may even be pos- sible, if circumstances permit, to render such a distinction using VCD alone without calculations in suitable cases if the bands are readily ascribable. DFT quantum chemical calculations were performed using Gaussian09 (version A.01) [22] and analyzed using the GUI Gauss- View (versions 3.07 and 5.0.8). Structures of (R)-prealnumycin (4) and alnumycin A1 (1) were geometry-optimized using the M06-2X hybrid meta density functional [23] with the 6-31G(d) basis set in tandem with vibrational analysis of harmonic frequencies and thermochemistry calculations at the same level of theory. Results and discussion 3.1. Structure optimization For (R)-prealnumycin (4), two stable conformers have previ- ously [1a] been found, one with an axially orientated n-propyl

group and the other with it equatorially orientated, from free-hand formulated starting structures. The conformer with the axially ori- entated n-propyl group was substantially lower in energy than the conformer with an equatorially orientated n-propyl group (DG(cid:3) = 4.4 kcal/mol) and hence only it was subsequently used as a starting unit for the alnumycin A1 (1) constructs. For the struc- tures of alnumycins A1a (1a) and A1b (1b) and the C-1 epimer of 1a (ent-1b), three conformations arising from rotation about the C8AC10 bond were located and optimized with a 10 C40 chair confor- mation for the dioxane ring in each case. Depictions of the opti- mized structures for 1a, 1b, and 4 are presented in Figs. 3–6 together with their relative energies and Boltzmann populations. For brevity, only the lowest energy conformer is presented for 1a and 1b (and since ent-1b is the enantiomer of 1b, it neither is shown); both the low- and the high-energy conformers of 4 are de- picted. For ent-1b, the calculated energy values were equal to or within ±0.01 kcal/mol of the calculated values for 1b.

In principle, if VCD bands can be unambiguously ascribed to a particular portion of the molecule in which the stereogenic centers are contained, then differentiation between the cases can poten- tially be effected since they can indicate whether that portion of the molecule in terms of its stereogenic center(s) is ‘‘holemic’’ or ‘‘racemic’’. This can apply to any chirooptical or other changes and in fact applies to these compounds in the case of the ECD [1] and the CDA [1b] results. A general rule has been stated: ‘‘If there are chirooptical or other changes in properties dominated by or local- ized to particular portions containing the stereogenic centers which are subject to the local chirality, then these can provide an indication of whether there is present a case of epimers or inverse epimers.’’ [1a]. An idealized hypothetical example of VCD based on this premise is visualized in Fig. 7 with particular bands serving to indicate the stereochemistry of each portion of the molecule (with alnumycin A substructures being used merely as a representative chiral sys- tem). For example, a pair of C-1 epimers would yield sets of bands such as A and D for one epimer and B and D for the other epimer; a pair of C-1 inverse epimers on the other hand might yield A and D for one inverse epimer and A and E for the other inverse epimer. For equal mixtures of compounds, bands of opposing sign will lead to cancellation, thus for a pair of C-1 epimers a nulled set such as C might result in addition to retention of the set D for the other por- tion of the molecules; alternatively, for a pair of C-1 inverse epi- mers, instead of a band set D being present, a nulled set F might result but with retention of the band set A. Thus, compounds could have their relative relationships readily ascertained based on observations ﬁtting to the appropriate case. Fig. 7. To further explore this notion in principle, the VCD bands for the two low-energy conformers in each case of alnumycins A1a (1a) and A1b (1b) and the C-1 epimer of 1a (ent-1b) as well as (R)-pre- alnumycin (4) were calculated. The calculated VCD data of the HAO, HAC, and C@C m bands – deemed the most interesting and indicative for these structures by inspection of the full spectra – are presented in Table 1. The designation of suitability of bands as being amenable to epimer–inverse epimer differentiation was gov- erned by criteria such as distinctiveness from other signals, rotary strength, identiﬁability, and assignability to recognizable vibra- tions. For example, quite distinct spectra (partial spectra for the re- gions covering the HAO, HAC, C@C, and C@O m bands over the ranges of 3600–2900 cm(cid:3)1 and 1875–1525 cm(cid:3)1 are portrayed in Fig. 8) were calculated for the two conformers of (R)-prealnumycin (4) as beﬁts their disparate structures, though some bands almost seem to be suggestive of an inherent ‘‘opposite conﬁguration’’ for the two structures, e.g. the HAO-10 m bands in the range 3450– 3500 cm(cid:3)1 and the C@C m bands at ca. 1630 and 1550 cm(cid:3)1. This re- sult can actually have an underlying structural basis rather than simply be a nominal coincidence given that the skews of the isoch- romanequinone motif in the two conformers are near mirror images of each other and which have been held to account for the predicted near mirror image ECD spectra for the two conformers [1a]. Two observations of note, ﬁrstly, the HAO-10 m bands do not fully match each other with respect to opposing intensity, thus they will not completely null each other if the two species were present in equal amounts. This is due to the isochromanequinone motifs not being perfect mirror images of each other in the two conformers. However,

m bands do not fully match each other with respect to opposing intensity, thus they will not completely null each other if the two species were present in equal amounts. This is due to the isochromanequinone motifs not being perfect mirror images of each other in the two conformers. However, this consideration is of only limited concern for the alnumycins A1a (1a) and A1b (1b) and the C-1 epimer of 1a (ent- 1b) as the separate moieties – the dioxane ring and the isochroman- equinone motif – have only limited engagement with each other apart from the adjoining C10AC8 bond and the stereogenic centers are also well separated, leading to the supposition that each moiety is its own isolated chiral entity. This is the basis for the aforemen- tioned postulate. The other observation of note is that the frequen- cies neither match well, though such a disparity would be less evident in the ECD as a consequence of the broad bands which are likely to obscure such minor differences.

The promising results indicated in Table 1 and by (R)-prealnu- mycin (4) thus provided the impetus for further examination and from the output of the spectral visualizations, ﬁnal aggregate VCD spectra for alnumycins A1a (1a) and A1b (1b) and the C-1 epi- mer of 1a (ent-1b) were appropriately population-weighted aver- aged (PWA) according to their Boltzmann distribution based on the calculated DG(cid:3) values for the two major contributing conform- ers [24]. The addition of spectra consisting of equal contributions of the PWA spectra of 1a and 1b, and of the PWA spectra 1a and ent-1b then followed. In Fig. 9 for the region covering the C@C and C@O m bands in the range 1925–1525 cm(cid:3)1, the prominent bands such as the aromatic ring m antisym, C5a@C9a and C4a@C10a m sym, C5@C5a and C10@C10a m sym, and C3@C4 m are essentially identical for the two PWA spectra of alnumycins A1 (1a) and A1b (1b) as their characteristics are gov- erned by the C-1 conﬁguration, which determines the adopted skewed conformation and consequent stereostructure. This pre- mise can be ascertained from the analogous conformation of (R)- prealnumycin (4) with an axially oriented n-propyl group where a similar set of bands are obtained to the PWA spectra of 1a and 1b, albeit with increased intensity for some of the other bands. In the other conformation for 4 which possesses an opposite skew for the isochromanequinone unit, the bands are all inversed except for C3@C4 m which is essentially nulled, thereby indicating that it is not just the C-1 conﬁguration and resultant skew that dictates the band characteristics, but also other subtle nuances imparted by the adopted conformation. Thus bands pertaining to the dioxane unit can also potentially provide an indication of a case of epimers or inverse epimers.

Thus, the proof-of-principle is clear by this evaluation of various bands for both regions of the alnumycin structure covering, or at least governed by, the conﬁgurations of the stereogenic centers in the prealnumycin unit and the dioxane moiety. With clear band assignment and association to one local or the other, VCD can potentially be used to distinguish between a case of epimers or in- verse epimers. The quandary arises because the epimer and the in- thus verse indistinguishable outside of a chiral environment and bearing the same relationship to the compound in question. The unlikely par- adox here is that the nominal pursuit at least of absolute conﬁgu- ration – though not necessarily assigning it – is being made in order to effect the determination of a relative conﬁguration rela- tionship. The determination of the absolute conﬁguration will clearly arise if both resolution and assignment permit, or if the rel- ative contents of the sample itself permit (with or without resolu- tion). In principle, only a single band may be all that is required to determine the epimer/inverse epimer case experimentally, though obviously a set of consistent results can provide unequivocal con- ﬁrmation. Furthermore, recourse to molecular modeling for some systems may not even be necessary to effect distinction between a case of epimers or inverse epimers after measurement if one can unambiguously and uniquely ascribe bands to portions of the molecule containing either the stereogenic center in question or the remaining set of stereogenic centers, and this could well be the prevailing state here based on the inference of these results. Thus, for the system considered here, viz. alnumycin A1 (1), DFT- calculated spectra have provided positive indications regarding the capability of VCD to effect distinction between a case of epi- mers or inverse epimers and hence for it to be a successful means of solving the dilemma.
